1
00:00:02,711 --> 00:00:04,912
Hello, welcome to my talk.

2
00:00:06,312 --> 00:00:09,453
It's titled, It Takes Two to Tango,

3
00:00:10,334 --> 00:00:12,775
Integrating UX Research and Production at EA.

4
00:00:14,495 --> 00:00:19,437
So this presentation is about how we learn to dance together.

5
00:00:21,038 --> 00:00:22,478
One dancer is production.

6
00:00:23,318 --> 00:00:24,899
The other dancer is research.

7
00:00:26,380 --> 00:00:29,961
When you start learning how to dance, you're not good at it.

8
00:00:31,557 --> 00:00:34,958
You step into toes, ones go to one side,

9
00:00:35,018 --> 00:00:36,498
the other goes to the other side.

10
00:00:36,518 --> 00:00:39,179
The two dancers are going to make mistakes.

11
00:00:40,439 --> 00:00:43,060
Like in dancing, you're constantly moving.

12
00:00:43,740 --> 00:00:45,240
Like in development games too,

13
00:00:45,580 --> 00:00:47,881
you're constantly producing, iterating,

14
00:00:47,921 --> 00:00:48,961
you're always moving.

15
00:00:49,781 --> 00:00:52,802
There is no time to stop, keep things coming.

16
00:00:54,923 --> 00:00:57,003
And it takes practice to get good at it.

17
00:00:58,684 --> 00:01:00,664
So, how these two dancers met.

18
00:01:02,445 --> 00:01:05,207
User experience has been getting a lot of traction

19
00:01:05,227 --> 00:01:07,829
during the last couple of years within the game industry.

20
00:01:08,689 --> 00:01:11,291
You could say that it's one of the newest aspects

21
00:01:11,591 --> 00:01:12,932
within game development.

22
00:01:14,193 --> 00:01:17,035
For instance, here we are, GDC.

23
00:01:17,676 --> 00:01:19,857
It is 29th iteration,

24
00:01:20,438 --> 00:01:22,699
and this is the first time there is a UX summit.

25
00:01:23,580 --> 00:01:24,801
That alone is very telling.

26
00:01:26,943 --> 00:01:30,025
Yet, UX as a concept was coined in the 90s.

27
00:01:31,528 --> 00:01:32,128
by Norman.

28
00:01:32,849 --> 00:01:34,991
It actually, history of testing usability

29
00:01:35,031 --> 00:01:36,693
goes all the way back to the 40s.

30
00:01:37,153 --> 00:01:40,056
So there has been a long history of measuring and assessing

31
00:01:41,157 --> 00:01:43,339
user experience in a variety of products,

32
00:01:44,721 --> 00:01:45,802
particularly in games.

33
00:01:46,742 --> 00:01:49,484
You have heard about playtesting for a long time.

34
00:01:50,385 --> 00:01:55,209
However, such concept has been used in a variety of ways

35
00:01:55,649 --> 00:01:58,071
and generally without the framework of research.

36
00:01:58,892 --> 00:02:00,774
And I'll dive more in depth about this

37
00:02:01,074 --> 00:02:02,175
throughout the presentation.

38
00:02:04,937 --> 00:02:07,920
Nowadays, every major developer

39
00:02:08,440 --> 00:02:12,123
has a dedicated UX research staff.

40
00:02:13,610 --> 00:02:19,096
I surveyed these numbers mid-2016 and I sorted them out alphabetically.

41
00:02:20,417 --> 00:02:22,579
Notice that some of them are quite sizable.

42
00:02:23,160 --> 00:02:27,344
It could be the equivalent for a whole company or to a development team in itself.

43
00:02:29,195 --> 00:02:34,178
And moreover, as our understanding of player experience matures,

44
00:02:34,699 --> 00:02:38,422
multiple disciplines are consolidating within larger departments.

45
00:02:39,042 --> 00:02:43,365
And this is the case for Electronic Arts, Riot, and Ubisoft,

46
00:02:44,406 --> 00:02:49,550
where games user research, analytics, market research, and data science

47
00:02:50,190 --> 00:02:52,111
are part of an internal larger organization.

48
00:02:54,569 --> 00:03:01,632
However, during the advent of UX research into game development, production might have

49
00:03:01,772 --> 00:03:07,855
been seeing research as a disruption to process that they have already established.

50
00:03:09,416 --> 00:03:15,059
While UX researchers were still adapting their methods and their vocabulary for game development

51
00:03:15,119 --> 00:03:15,659
contexts.

52
00:03:16,784 --> 00:03:23,430
And that interruption took many shapes, from production not seeing the need for research,

53
00:03:23,890 --> 00:03:28,355
to production wanting, but not knowing how to action on those findings.

54
00:03:29,836 --> 00:03:36,863
Mind you, it was also for research to know how to convey those UX findings in a timely

55
00:03:36,903 --> 00:03:41,408
manner, and how to communicate it in such a way that were meaningful and actionable.

56
00:03:42,501 --> 00:03:44,583
And this is part of the story I'm going to tell you today.

57
00:03:45,383 --> 00:03:48,565
When UX research are designed and not fully synchronized,

58
00:03:49,166 --> 00:03:51,007
it leads to missing UX opportunities.

59
00:03:51,948 --> 00:03:55,290
And opportunities doesn't mean that they

60
00:03:55,350 --> 00:03:57,032
have to be a major overhaul.

61
00:03:57,572 --> 00:04:01,235
Opportunities are also within production's limitations

62
00:04:01,835 --> 00:04:06,279
of time, budget, scope, and technology.

63
00:04:09,901 --> 00:04:11,342
And why I'm telling you all this?

64
00:04:12,170 --> 00:04:14,291
Well, my name is Veronica Zamito.

65
00:04:14,971 --> 00:04:17,812
I'm the lead senior UX researcher at Electronic Arts.

66
00:04:18,472 --> 00:04:20,732
And over the last seven years, I've

67
00:04:20,752 --> 00:04:24,013
had the opportunity of working on amazing games

68
00:04:24,933 --> 00:04:26,113
of the EA portfolio.

69
00:04:27,054 --> 00:04:28,974
And today I'm going to be sharing with you

70
00:04:29,334 --> 00:04:32,895
the stories on how we tackle UX research and production

71
00:04:33,375 --> 00:04:34,655
integration at EA.

72
00:04:37,716 --> 00:04:38,576
Spoiler alert.

73
00:04:39,536 --> 00:04:40,316
This is how we are now.

74
00:04:41,212 --> 00:04:42,994
This is what happens at the end of the story.

75
00:04:44,835 --> 00:04:47,577
UX Research at EA is a sizable team.

76
00:04:48,158 --> 00:04:52,041
We're geographically distributed across eight locations worldwide.

77
00:04:53,061 --> 00:04:55,783
And at EA, we have three prototypical tasks.

78
00:04:56,524 --> 00:05:00,407
We have researchers, recruiters, and lab technicians.

79
00:05:02,168 --> 00:05:04,070
Depending on the size of the company,

80
00:05:04,650 --> 00:05:07,953
all those roles can be carried out by different people

81
00:05:09,194 --> 00:05:10,174
or by a single person.

82
00:05:11,902 --> 00:05:18,503
The latter happens more often in smaller companies or at early stages of UX research teams.

83
00:05:19,623 --> 00:05:21,164
And that was actually my case.

84
00:05:21,624 --> 00:05:27,125
Back in the day when I started UX research at EA, I had to do my own recruitment while

85
00:05:27,165 --> 00:05:29,626
designing the sessions and setting up the lab.

86
00:05:29,646 --> 00:05:31,986
That was a lot of struggling.

87
00:05:33,075 --> 00:05:37,259
So imagine that each task takes time away from the other one.

88
00:05:38,060 --> 00:05:40,743
And it's not that they have to be done in sequential order.

89
00:05:41,363 --> 00:05:46,028
So it's quite exhausting and it's actually not efficient.

90
00:05:48,951 --> 00:05:52,314
Now with SIDA, we do have certain philosophies

91
00:05:52,935 --> 00:05:57,159
that actually define and help the way that we want to work.

92
00:05:58,165 --> 00:06:03,209
So we aspire to work as one team across multiple studios.

93
00:06:05,051 --> 00:06:08,374
And actually, what's at the forefront of our job is

94
00:06:08,454 --> 00:06:10,355
players, so it's players first.

95
00:06:12,657 --> 00:06:14,438
And all these things might sound great.

96
00:06:14,999 --> 00:06:15,919
It's actually great.

97
00:06:16,980 --> 00:06:20,883
But it wasn't with many bumps on the road and misalignments

98
00:06:20,923 --> 00:06:22,825
at first until we got there.

99
00:06:24,947 --> 00:06:26,828
So how did we get there?

100
00:06:28,253 --> 00:06:33,015
Well, first and foremost, we didn't get that overnight.

101
00:06:34,555 --> 00:06:36,196
It was a multi-year journey.

102
00:06:36,916 --> 00:06:39,557
And sincerely, it's a path that will never end.

103
00:06:40,577 --> 00:06:44,538
As the UX practice, the industry, and products evolve,

104
00:06:44,998 --> 00:06:46,799
we will have to evolve as part of that.

105
00:06:48,139 --> 00:06:50,180
And in this talk, I'll share those examples,

106
00:06:50,260 --> 00:06:54,681
those lessons learned that shape, thriving, and integrated

107
00:06:54,881 --> 00:06:55,882
the UX practice.

108
00:06:57,772 --> 00:07:02,514
This is a journey with key milestones, and I'm going to go through those.

109
00:07:05,015 --> 00:07:08,436
It starts rough, and it starts with a wake-up call.

110
00:07:10,577 --> 00:07:14,779
Back in 2009, the NBA elite was being developed.

111
00:07:16,019 --> 00:07:19,241
Improving UX was a huge driver for that team.

112
00:07:20,321 --> 00:07:21,661
There were high expectations.

113
00:07:23,085 --> 00:07:25,485
They were introducing a brand new set of controls,

114
00:07:25,926 --> 00:07:27,486
mechanics new to EVO.

115
00:07:27,726 --> 00:07:31,567
It was meant to be a reboot of the NBA Live franchise.

116
00:07:32,468 --> 00:07:35,129
And consequently, the game team was very self-aware

117
00:07:35,169 --> 00:07:38,930
of the quality of the UX data and how actionable it was.

118
00:07:40,250 --> 00:07:45,292
At the time, playtesting was part of development process.

119
00:07:46,132 --> 00:07:49,253
However, it was led by designers and producers

120
00:07:49,313 --> 00:07:52,374
who self-taught themselves how to do usability.

121
00:07:53,827 --> 00:07:57,009
And even though they have the best intentions in the world,

122
00:07:57,609 --> 00:08:00,231
they could smell that something could be better,

123
00:08:00,311 --> 00:08:01,852
something could be done differently.

124
00:08:01,872 --> 00:08:06,555
And that was the seed of starting from transforming

125
00:08:06,976 --> 00:08:09,317
play testing into UX research.

126
00:08:11,439 --> 00:08:15,802
In 2010, we started initiatives for new approaches

127
00:08:16,102 --> 00:08:19,084
to evaluate NBA with players

128
00:08:19,644 --> 00:08:20,905
and bringing the edge of science.

129
00:08:24,813 --> 00:08:29,476
For that, I went super tech and I brought advanced techniques

130
00:08:30,156 --> 00:08:33,138
that it was the first time doing that for play testing.

131
00:08:33,598 --> 00:08:37,000
So we're using eye tracking and biometrics and telemetry

132
00:08:37,060 --> 00:08:41,722
and all of those at once to assess visual attention,

133
00:08:41,942 --> 00:08:45,404
emotional valence, tracking their in-game behaviors.

134
00:08:46,865 --> 00:08:47,705
It was awesome.

135
00:08:49,306 --> 00:08:52,908
The idea behind that was to tap into insights

136
00:08:53,368 --> 00:08:54,108
that surveys.

137
00:08:55,023 --> 00:08:55,563
couldn't get.

138
00:08:56,764 --> 00:08:59,365
And the effort was to give the most we could to NBA

139
00:08:59,425 --> 00:09:01,205
for understanding the player experience.

140
00:09:03,606 --> 00:09:05,987
There was a particular fascinating finding

141
00:09:06,368 --> 00:09:08,569
that players consistently looked at the coach

142
00:09:08,629 --> 00:09:09,689
after making a basket.

143
00:09:10,429 --> 00:09:13,571
And bear in mind, the coach was there in the background

144
00:09:14,011 --> 00:09:15,431
doing nothing.

145
00:09:16,727 --> 00:09:20,711
No animation, no voiceovers, anything that could lead to him.

146
00:09:21,512 --> 00:09:27,117
So it was very unexpected and pointed out a missed opportunity for positive reinforcement.

147
00:09:29,179 --> 00:09:31,441
That insight never appeared with any other technique.

148
00:09:33,723 --> 00:09:39,489
I was getting insights that were completely new on that approach and all this marvelous

149
00:09:39,629 --> 00:09:39,909
work.

150
00:09:40,879 --> 00:09:45,082
was new, so the process was a little bit slow,

151
00:09:45,542 --> 00:09:48,885
and actually, those findings couldn't be done.

152
00:09:48,925 --> 00:09:50,246
There was no automation.

153
00:09:50,266 --> 00:09:51,867
It was very labor-intensive.

154
00:09:52,368 --> 00:09:55,590
So findings like those needed to be left for discussion

155
00:09:55,670 --> 00:09:58,072
for a next installment of NBA.

156
00:09:59,974 --> 00:10:01,095
Time was passing by,

157
00:10:01,115 --> 00:10:04,397
and the team needed to focus on finishing the game.

158
00:10:05,618 --> 00:10:07,940
And NBA Elite was coming hot.

159
00:10:09,833 --> 00:10:14,156
As it's common, there was a demo scheduled and released to the public.

160
00:10:15,397 --> 00:10:21,581
And I'm going to show you next some snippets from a video that went viral of a player playing

161
00:10:21,601 --> 00:10:22,041
the demo.

162
00:10:28,026 --> 00:10:34,550
One thing I didn't like, they make you play in the up and down view.

163
00:10:34,630 --> 00:10:36,892
I really don't like that fucking up and down view.

164
00:10:36,972 --> 00:10:37,692
Oh, I can change it?

165
00:10:37,732 --> 00:10:38,513
We'll change that shit.

166
00:10:40,035 --> 00:10:41,316
Broadcast, there we go.

167
00:10:41,496 --> 00:10:45,037
I didn't even know you could change it, I just noticed that.

168
00:10:45,077 --> 00:10:45,677
You did?

169
00:10:46,577 --> 00:10:48,798
What the fuck is going on?

170
00:10:48,918 --> 00:10:53,139
Hold up man, there's something wrong with my goddamn buttons.

171
00:10:53,179 --> 00:10:54,159
This shit is crazy.

172
00:10:54,639 --> 00:11:06,342
I didn't have it on my lead, that's what it was.

173
00:11:06,482 --> 00:11:09,083
Alright, let's go.

174
00:11:11,315 --> 00:11:13,116
The response time to the buttons is slow as fuck.

175
00:11:13,137 --> 00:11:14,017
What's that about?

176
00:11:14,117 --> 00:11:18,922
These controls are crazy. You gotta get used to these controls.

177
00:11:18,942 --> 00:11:23,546
This is crazy, man. I haven't played live in so long.

178
00:11:23,566 --> 00:11:24,307
What the fuck?

179
00:11:24,327 --> 00:11:26,569
Yo, y'all seeing this shit?

180
00:11:39,714 --> 00:11:41,354
Yo, what the fuck?

181
00:11:41,495 --> 00:11:46,355
This nigga just standing like Jesus in the middle of the court.

182
00:11:46,435 --> 00:11:50,856
Oh my God, man. That's it for the demo, man.

183
00:11:50,916 --> 00:11:53,417
I can't take no more of this shit, man.

184
00:11:53,537 --> 00:11:55,037
It's hard these times, man.

185
00:11:55,057 --> 00:11:56,057
Deuces, man. Deuces.

186
00:11:56,137 --> 00:12:00,378
That was a funny video, but...

187
00:12:02,518 --> 00:12:05,059
There were obviously friction points in the UI.

188
00:12:05,099 --> 00:12:06,839
There were friction points in the mechanic.

189
00:12:07,959 --> 00:12:11,781
And this demo actually was a nail in the coffin.

190
00:12:11,801 --> 00:12:16,844
NBA Elite never ended up being released.

191
00:12:17,824 --> 00:12:20,706
It was deemed that it didn't reach the desired quality,

192
00:12:21,447 --> 00:12:22,787
that players would be disappointed,

193
00:12:23,188 --> 00:12:27,010
and that the best decision was to not release it at all.

194
00:12:28,431 --> 00:12:31,172
It was an extremely hard decision,

195
00:12:31,733 --> 00:12:34,254
and I cannot stress enough how much of a shock

196
00:12:34,334 --> 00:12:35,195
it was for everyone.

197
00:12:37,438 --> 00:12:38,339
It was a wake-up call.

198
00:12:39,540 --> 00:12:43,743
As a video game company, it was very clear that quality

199
00:12:43,843 --> 00:12:45,184
process needed to be better.

200
00:12:46,886 --> 00:12:51,049
And I wouldn't go as far as saying, oh, better UX research.

201
00:12:51,089 --> 00:12:52,950
We have been the silver bullet for this.

202
00:12:53,590 --> 00:12:55,072
There were other problems.

203
00:12:55,392 --> 00:12:59,615
But definitely, clear and more iterative UX

204
00:12:59,675 --> 00:13:01,516
checkpoints needed to be there.

205
00:13:03,359 --> 00:13:08,984
With that, the new UX research initiatives were a business case to bring to the next level.

206
00:13:11,426 --> 00:13:12,707
And there was work to be done.

207
00:13:13,468 --> 00:13:16,411
We needed to improve the research practice from its foundations.

208
00:13:17,092 --> 00:13:19,854
Even though biometrics techniques proved to be very insightful,

209
00:13:20,395 --> 00:13:26,140
we needed to change focus from advancing methodologies to establishing a UX process.

210
00:13:27,618 --> 00:13:33,160
We needed quality research in an iterative process where production and research are

211
00:13:33,220 --> 00:13:34,220
fully synchronized.

212
00:13:35,061 --> 00:13:38,221
That means having a plan, knowing your steps.

213
00:13:39,422 --> 00:13:41,502
We tackled this problem from three different angles.

214
00:13:42,363 --> 00:13:49,665
Strengthening the good research practice from a macro as well as from a micro level of research

215
00:13:49,705 --> 00:13:50,905
and production integration.

216
00:13:53,366 --> 00:13:55,906
Regarding the basic good research practice.

217
00:13:56,872 --> 00:14:01,136
There were imminent aspects to address, such as quality data,

218
00:14:01,737 --> 00:14:04,479
things like ensuring wording of questions in service

219
00:14:04,559 --> 00:14:05,900
are clean and not leading.

220
00:14:06,661 --> 00:14:09,463
These efforts were towards researcher skills,

221
00:14:10,204 --> 00:14:12,806
and the goal was to have quality data.

222
00:14:13,767 --> 00:14:17,410
So we have been certain that the research findings are good,

223
00:14:17,891 --> 00:14:19,252
and that also leads to trust.

224
00:14:20,353 --> 00:14:23,776
Trust from production, it's key.

225
00:14:25,176 --> 00:14:26,597
They don't have to double check the data,

226
00:14:26,617 --> 00:14:28,258
they don't feel they have to go themselves.

227
00:14:30,339 --> 00:14:32,880
The entrust is the cornerstone for any relationship.

228
00:14:34,621 --> 00:14:36,963
But ultimately, doing research

229
00:14:37,623 --> 00:14:39,284
is to communicate those findings.

230
00:14:40,485 --> 00:14:44,547
And like in tango, communication has to be clear and timely

231
00:14:45,648 --> 00:14:47,089
because you're constantly moving.

232
00:14:47,489 --> 00:14:49,850
You don't want your partner to go that way and you that way

233
00:14:50,751 --> 00:14:52,752
or accidentally step into each other's toes.

234
00:14:53,943 --> 00:14:56,405
So I'll show you one example on this topic.

235
00:14:57,505 --> 00:15:01,427
And you'll have seen research data coming in this form

236
00:15:01,447 --> 00:15:04,749
of prototypical question and a scale from one to five,

237
00:15:05,430 --> 00:15:09,051
all player data aggregated and presented in a bar chart

238
00:15:09,091 --> 00:15:14,154
like this, which is okay to know how good or bad things are.

239
00:15:15,015 --> 00:15:18,777
However, it's not sufficient if you want to prioritize

240
00:15:19,337 --> 00:15:20,878
resources in production.

241
00:15:22,550 --> 00:15:31,253
In cases when you have to look at multiple variables and do comparisons.

242
00:15:32,734 --> 00:15:39,416
This is the case in Plants vs. Zombies Garden Warfare, where there were more than 40 characters

243
00:15:39,936 --> 00:15:41,057
that you have to choose from.

244
00:15:41,817 --> 00:15:45,198
And productions wanted to ensure that all of them were hitting a mark,

245
00:15:45,859 --> 00:15:47,959
and if not, focus on those first.

246
00:15:49,060 --> 00:15:51,621
And that was exactly the question that we had, which was great.

247
00:15:53,090 --> 00:15:56,214
And looking to communicate findings, we look at different ways.

248
00:15:56,434 --> 00:16:01,259
We put some tables, so now you can really see the spread of responses.

249
00:16:02,320 --> 00:16:04,242
And even though the game team was happy with this,

250
00:16:05,023 --> 00:16:07,605
you can start to see that it's getting too hard to read.

251
00:16:07,986 --> 00:16:10,708
And when you have 40 columns of those,

252
00:16:11,069 --> 00:16:12,750
you cannot see through that clutter.

253
00:16:13,892 --> 00:16:14,092
So...

254
00:16:15,717 --> 00:16:21,198
That's why confidence intervals were becoming a part of

