00:23:00,838 --> 00:23:05,362
And with this, I'm referring to where within the company

374
00:23:05,722 --> 00:23:07,344
should UX research live.

375
00:23:08,344 --> 00:23:11,687
And organizational structures have implications

376
00:23:12,047 --> 00:23:15,810
on relationships, visibility for the product,

377
00:23:17,091 --> 00:23:20,174
and how you're going to be prioritizing content.

378
00:23:22,002 --> 00:23:25,105
At EA, we had a centralized UX research organization.

379
00:23:26,166 --> 00:23:29,329
We engaged with multiple game teams across all EA.

380
00:23:30,030 --> 00:23:33,232
And as you know, the EA portfolio is pretty large.

381
00:23:34,113 --> 00:23:40,339
So in other words, we have a single team with just a handful of researchers carrying out

382
00:23:40,739 --> 00:23:43,622
all the research activities for the whole organization.

383
00:23:44,625 --> 00:23:50,127
This means that the researcher was A, no part of the

384
00:23:50,147 --> 00:23:52,928
development team, and that the researcher was supporting

385
00:23:52,968 --> 00:23:54,149
multiple franchises.

386
00:23:54,969 --> 00:23:58,751
For instance, someone would be working on FIFA, as well as

387
00:23:58,931 --> 00:24:00,531
UFC and NHL.

388
00:24:03,292 --> 00:24:06,654
This type of organizational model was great for us at the

389
00:24:06,694 --> 00:24:06,974
time.

390
00:24:07,874 --> 00:24:08,975
Remember that wake-up call?

391
00:24:10,643 --> 00:24:12,565
We need a good sense of processes.

392
00:24:13,206 --> 00:24:15,668
So this organizational model was great for that.

393
00:24:16,488 --> 00:24:16,869
Why?

394
00:24:16,889 --> 00:24:20,151
There are like four key positive aspects for this.

395
00:24:22,193 --> 00:24:28,098
For once, it creates a really high, strong hub of experts.

396
00:24:28,839 --> 00:24:31,901
This allows a lot of easy sharing of best practices,

397
00:24:32,362 --> 00:24:36,625
reinforcing that quality, which was very important

398
00:24:36,645 --> 00:24:37,826
to mature our practice.

399
00:24:39,061 --> 00:24:44,883
The range of projects was varied, so it kept entertaining and refreshing, which for retaining

400
00:24:44,983 --> 00:24:46,964
talent long term can be important.

401
00:24:49,065 --> 00:24:56,468
The accumulation of knowledge across the different products allow us to have meta insights.

402
00:24:57,168 --> 00:25:01,730
If we put all our shooters together, all our sports together, we can answer bigger business

403
00:25:01,850 --> 00:25:02,771
questions for this.

404
00:25:04,103 --> 00:25:07,004
And ultimately, it has an economical benefit too,

405
00:25:07,584 --> 00:25:10,325
because central teams can share those resources.

406
00:25:11,285 --> 00:25:14,306
You don't need to build like two labs, three labs.

407
00:25:14,606 --> 00:25:16,607
You can license products.

408
00:25:16,687 --> 00:25:18,968
You can have your recruiter, your lab technician

409
00:25:19,008 --> 00:25:20,108
that serves everyone.

410
00:25:21,528 --> 00:25:23,689
So that was great for us.

411
00:25:24,709 --> 00:25:27,990
And with a handful of people, we need to cover a lot of games.

412
00:25:28,670 --> 00:25:30,291
And that's where some challenges are.

413
00:25:32,791 --> 00:25:34,893
We have to rationalize efforts.

414
00:25:35,774 --> 00:25:38,597
We have one person with three titles, three big titles.

415
00:25:38,737 --> 00:25:41,700
Well, we covered them all, but it's still one person.

416
00:25:43,482 --> 00:25:47,306
And that leads to a constant reprioritization exercise

417
00:25:47,346 --> 00:25:49,468
of the portfolio, which can be tricky,

418
00:25:50,029 --> 00:25:52,632
because it has implication of what's important,

419
00:25:52,652 --> 00:25:54,313
what's not important, what we should tackle.

420
00:25:55,305 --> 00:25:57,047
And you don't need a big portfolio.

421
00:25:57,307 --> 00:25:59,628
I'm pretty sure that all you can relate to this

